ese tradition. His work will be read and studied for years to come.The original essays presented here, which are substantive philosophical contributions in their own right, cover the full range of Ames's scholarly output. They address methodological questions as well as specific issues in textual interpretation, including ample discussion of Ames's most recent and provocative contribution: Confucian "role ethics." In the final section of the book, Ames responds to each essay. The result is a conversation and engagement that both underscores the vitality of his thinking and indicates the directions it may take in the future. Altogether, this work provides a snapshot of a remarkable career—and an invitation to continue reflecting upon its meaning and importance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPhilosophy, Chinese. 0aPhilosophy, Confucian. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Eastern / General.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngle, Stephen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehuniak, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehuniak, Jim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBell, Daniel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Kathleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasulis, Thomas P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Chenyang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoeller, Hans-Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeville, Robert Cummings, 